</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1185 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ELECTIONS ASSEMBLY; 
</P>
<P>
DISTRICT 45 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Overview 
</P>
<P>
Incumbent Assemblyman Burt Margolin, a Democrat, is strongly favored in the 
general election. His opponents have targeted his close ties to the 
Berman/Waxman organization, a powerful Westside-area political group headed by 
Reps. Howard L. Berman (D-Panorama City) and Henry A. Waxman (D-Los Angeles). 
The Republican primary has focused on the candidates' opposing views on 
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
Contenders 
</P>
<P>
Robert K. Davis, 45, a West Hollywood Republican, is a swimming pool contractor 
and former teacher who ran for the West Hollywood City Council in April. He is 
endorsed by the California Republican League and the Republicans' Gay and 
Lesbian Task Force. Davis' campaign has stressed getting out the vote, abortion 
rights and expanding the Republican Party to include more minorities. He holds 
a BA degree in social science from the State College of Iowa, and an MA in 
history from the University of Iowa. He is single. 
</P>
<P>
Elizabeth Michael, 33, a Los Angeles Republican, is an accounting and marketing 
consultant for small businesses. She ran unsuccessfully in the Republican 
primary for Sen. David Roberti's seat in the 23rd District two years ago. She 
is endorsed by the California Republican Assembly, and her campaign has focused 
on her opposition to gun control, abortion and malathion spraying. She received 
a BS degree in economics from the Wharton School of the University of 
Pennsylvania. She is single. 
</P>
<P>
Assemblyman Burt Margolin, a Los Angeles Democrat, and Owen Staley, a Peace and 
Freedom candidate, are unopposed in their primaries. 
</P>
<P>
Questionnaire 
</P>
<P>
Questionnaires were distributed to candidates and were returned this month. 
Answers have been edited to fit the available space. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Under recently introduced legislation, state sales taxes would be raised 
0.25% for 10 years to help finance school construction. Do you favor an 
increase in sales taxes to underwrite new school construction? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. An initiative measure on the June ballot would raise taxes on gasoline sales 
by 9 cents a gallon to finance highway projects. Do you support the concept of 
higher gas taxes to underwrite road construction? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No, not supporting Prop. 111. Supports concept of gas tax for road 
repair. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support a woman's unrestricted right to an abortion within the first 
three months of pregnancy? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support capital punishment? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support the idea of breaking up the Los Angeles Unified School 
District into smaller districts? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Under current law, the state Legislature is responsible for redrawing state 
legislative and congressional district boundaries. Do you believe this system 
should be changed? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes. Present ills are due to a stalemated political system; 
reapportionment is a key to ending this. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. I support Prop. 119, which puts redistricting in the hands of a 
citizens committee . . . instead of a corrupt legislature. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support the so-called "Big Green" ballot initiative, which would 
eliminate ozone-depleting chemicals by the year 2000, phase out pesticides 
known to cause cancer and require that trees be planted in all new 
developments? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you think the state should require private employers to subsidize 
day-care services for employees who request them? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. This is being worked out by employers. Would discourage employment. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. Good business, but should not be forced. Supports tax credit 
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support the state's efforts to build prisons in Lancaster and East 
Los Angeles? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Proposition 112 on the June ballot would ban speaking fees and limit gifts 
to state legislators while creating a commission that could pave the way for 
higher legislative salaries. Do you support this ballot initiative? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. Prefers speaker fees to a pay raise. No pay raise for a job poorly 
done. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Undecided. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support Gov. Deukmejian's proposed constitutional changes that would 
require state prison inmates to work in privately sponsored industries to pay 
for their incarceration? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes, but I'm not sure it will work. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you believe our present system of criminal prosecution, interdiction of 
supplies and imprisonment of users and dealers will ever significantly reduce 
the level of drug use in the United States? 
</P>
<P>
If no, what should be done? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. Only diminished demand will work. Best action is publicizing results 
of drug use. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. Education is key, and without God we will never solve society's 
drug problem. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Would you consider the possibility of decriminalizing the use of drugs? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No answer given. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support raising sales or other taxes to finance anti-drug law 
enforcement efforts and/or anti-drug education programs? 
</P>
<P>
If yes, by how much? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support full or partial public funding of political campaigns? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. Never read a proposal that seems workable. Also, we don't have the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. The public should not be forced to finance campaigns they disagree 
with. 
</P>
<P>
Q. A ballot initiative now in circulation would prohibit foreign individuals 
and corporations from owning land in California. Do you support this? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Rising property values in the Santa Monica Mountains have made it more 
difficult for state and federal parks agencies to buy land for public use. Land 
prices have escalated in part because local officials have allowed developers 
to build more houses than provided for under zoning laws. To keep property 
prices more affordable to parks agencies, should governments in Los Angeles and 
Ventura counties refuse such so-called "upzoning?" 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. An inherent conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Are you willing to publicly release your tax returns and those of your 
spouse before the election? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: No. It's an invasion of privacy. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. A development project called Porter Ranch would create 3,395 residential 
units and nearly 6 million square feet of commercial office space in the 
Chatsworth hills. Opponents say it is too big. Proponents say it represents 
orderly growth. Do you support the project at this size? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Undecided. Based on newspaper reports, I would probably support it. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: No. 
</P>
<P>
Q. Do you support limits on the number of terms state legislators can serve? 
</P>
<P>
If yes, how long should they be? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes. Assembly, three terms; Senate, two terms. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. Assembly, four terms; Senate, two terms. 
</P>
<P>
Q. A ballot initiative now in circulation would prohibit the spraying of 
pesticides on private property without the written consent of the owner. Do you 
support this measure? 
</P>
<P>
Davis: Yes, a welcome reassertion of property rights. 
</P>
<P>
Michael: Yes. I oppose malathion spraying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Davis ; Photo, Michael ; Map, Assembly District 45, MATT MOODY / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
