<HEADLINE>
<P>
IMPROVING POLITICAL CAMPAIGNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
If both parties want to reform campaign financing and coverage (front page, May 
7), the solution is simple. Since almost every dollar is spent on advertising, 
prohibit political advertising. 
</P>
<P>
It's not needed and, if the goal is to turn out the voters, it's a miserable 
failure. The higher the spending, the lower the voter turnout. 
</P>
<P>
Gorbachev has never advertised in the U.S. but his name, face and ideas are 
universally known. 
</P>
<P>
That may be the secret -- ideas. If candidates stop selling themselves like 
soap and breakfast cereal, they would have to command attention with substance 
instead of production values. 
</P>
<P>
If their ideas are compelling and plentiful enough, their day-to-day coverage 
would increase in ratio as would their TV guest appearances, debate 
invitations, and commentary page articles. Their personal exposure to the 
voters would come with innovative barnstorming enhanced -- if their ideas are 
newsworthy enough -- by regional exposure on television and newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
Campaigns could be run at a fraction of today's costs. All it takes is a ban on 
political advertising and insistence by the media for legitimate news instead 
of "photo ops." Who knows, voters might start voting again. 
</P>
<P>
One problem: How do you get the media to back an advertising ban? 
</P>
<P>
PHIL WILLON 
</P>
<P>
Palos Verdes Peninsula 
</P>
</TEXT>
