<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: ART 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kirk Douglas Collection Sold: "Chasse Croise," a painting of fantastic 
personages by Jean Dubuffet, sold for $2 million and ran away with an auction 
of 17 works from the collection of Kirk and Anne Douglas on Wednesday at 
Christie's New York. The couple put a total of 52 works on the block this month 
to raise funds for a collection of contemporary art. 
</P>
<P>
The Dubuffet and Bernard Buffet's "Fleur de Lis," which brought $385,000, were 
the only items that exceeded expectations. Eight pieces failed to sell and four 
fetched less than their low estimates. Among the sales were a painting of a 
white horse and Mexican rider by Marc Chagall ($660,000) and a Georges Braque 
still life ($638,000). GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051790-0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 219882 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
May 17, 1990, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Part F; Page 2; Column 2; Entertainment Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
354 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
MUSIC REVIEW; 
</P>
<P>
PIANIST DAVID ANDRUSS IN CONSERVATIVE PROGRAM IN ORANGE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN BLISS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ORANGE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At the St. Joseph Center Auditorium Tuesday night, 20-year-old pianist David 
Andruss took a tentative step toward building a career. 
</P>
<P>
The Southern California native, whose USC bachelor of music degree was just 5 
days old, had mounted a grass-roots campaign, rallying friends and family, who 
had arranged for the hall, orchestrated publicity, ordered printed programs and 
sold tickets. Tuesday they were manning the doors, assembling a mailing list 
and accepting orders for tapes of the recital. 
</P>
<P>
Andruss himself presented a conservative program -- perhaps (judging from the 
four historical periods faithfully represented) a replay of his graduation 
recital. Programming familiar works may endear the performer to his audience, 
but it also risks comparison to standards already set by great artists. 
</P>
<P>
Andruss is talented and ambitious, but he is not a great artist. His 
performance of Chopin's F-minor Ballade was clean, well-controlled and 
musically sensitive. But the piece's potential for emotional catharsis remained 
hidden. 
</P>
<P>
Other works also unfolded with refinement but with relatively little excitement 
and few profundities. The Fourth Partita of J.S. Bach opened with stylish 
double-dotting and liberal use of pedal. Andruss sang the Allemande lovingly, 
though without exploiting poignant dissonances. He phrased logically and found 
a bright, appealing sound in the Gigue. Still, he shunned varied ornamentation 
that might have enlivened repeats in slow movements. 
</P>
<P>
Andruss' straightforward attentiveness extended to mastery over dynamic nuance, 
especially softer shades. This served well in four quiet miniatures from 
Federico Mompou's suite of nine "Impresiones Intimas" and afforded some 
atmospheric Impressionism in Ravel's "Le Tombeau de Couperin." 
</P>
<P>
"Le Tombeau," which closed the concert, gave the only hint of a musical 
perception and showmanship that might surpass pleasant competence. Throughout 
the work, Andruss kept his tempos strict, his tone shimmering but unvaried. 
</P>
<P>
However, in the final movement, the Toccata, he built an exciting momentum and 
propelled the music toward an effective climax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Concert Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
