<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: THE REGION; 
</P>
<P>
TREATMENT PLANT INSTALLED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Workers on Tuesday began installing a $800,000 treatment plant to save a 
polluted Baldwin Park well. 
</P>
<P>
The well, on Maine Avenue near Irwindale, was polluted last year by 
carcinogenic compounds commonly used in industries and businesses. 
</P>
<P>
Water officials say the pollution stemmed from one of the four large plumes of 
contamination that plague large portions of the underground water supply of the 
San Gabriel Valley. 
</P>
<P>
The need for the treatment plant is heightened because of the drought, said 
Stanley D. Yarbrough, general manager the Valley County Water District, which 
is building the facility. "Without this project, the district's existing well 
supply is not going to be enough to meet the high demands during the hot summer 
months," he said. 
</P>
<P>
The district serves 40,000 residential and business customers in Baldwin Park, 
Irwindale and West Covina. Of the district's 10 wells, seven have been shut 
down because of pollution. To finance the project, the water district in 
February imposed a 25% rate increase, most of which will go toward the costs of 
the treatment plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
