<P>
EX-MONTOYA AIDE PLEADS GUILTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire ServicesSTATE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A former top aide to ex-Sen. Joseph Montoya pleaded guilty today to one felony 
count of lying on a home loan application, as prosecutors dismissed four 
corruption charges stemming from the FBI's undercover probe of the Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
Amiel Jaramillo, 36, entered the plea before U.S. District Judge Milton 
Schwartz, who set sentencing for July 26. 
</P>
<P>
Jaramillo pleaded guilty to concealing debts totaling $18,000 in outstanding 
student loans in a February, 1987, home loan application to the Veterans 
Administration. The loan was later approved. 
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors said the count on which Jaramillo pleaded guilty was a new charge 
not related to the Montoya case. It carries a penalty of up to five years in 
prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
