<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE SIDELINES; 
</P>
<P>
BRITISH IDENTIFY SOCCER ROWDIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The British government sent a list of convicted soccer hooligans to Italian 
authorities today and recommended that the rowdy fans be barred from attending 
World Cup matches next month. 
</P>
<P>
The announcement by Home Secretary David Waddington, whose department is 
responsible for law and order in Britain, came one day after a flare-up of fan 
violence at an English soccer match. 
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight people were charged with assault and other offenses after running 
onto the field Wednesday night in Newcastle during a playoff game against 
Sunderland. Nine police officers were injured in battles with fans. 
</P>
<P>
More than 100 fans were arrested at several games around England on May 5, the 
final day of the English Soccer League season, with the worst violence and 
property destruction in the southern coastal city of Bournemouth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
