<HEADLINE>
<P>
H. COHEN, 95, EX-OWNER OF PIMLICO, DIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BALTIMORE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Herman Cohen, president of Pimlico race course from 1952 until he sold it in 
1986, died today at age 95. 
</P>
<P>
Cohen had cancer. 
</P>
<P>
His death came just two days before the 115th running of the Preakness, second 
jewel of the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
Four years ago, Cohen sold the track to Frank De Francis, who died in August. 
</P>
<P>
Since the sale, Cohen operated a Baltimore land developing and construction 
business with his younger brother, 90-year-old Ben Cohen. 
</P>
<P>
Cohen also raced and bred thoroughbreds, and he was a past director of the 
Thoroughbred Racing Assn. 
</P>
<P>
He is survived by his wife, Grace, two brothers, a sister, two grandchildren 
and a niece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
